{"title_page": "Contagious disease", "text_new": "{{expert needed | Medicine|date = September 2016}}\n{{Refimprove|date= September 2016}}\n\nA '''contagious disease''' is a subset category of [[Transmission (medicine)|transmissible]] [[diseases]], which are transmitted to other persons, either by physical contact with the person suffering the disease, or by casual contact with their [[secretion]]s or objects touched by them or [[airborne disease|airborne route]] among other routes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/Contagious+disease |title=Merriam-Webster dictionary definition of contagious disease |access-date=2009-11-27}}</ref>  Contagiousness varies between diseases.\n\nNon-contagious infections, by contrast, usually require a special mode of transmission between persons or [[host (biology)|host]]s. These include need for intermediate [[vector (epidemiology)|vector]] species ([[mosquito]]es that carry [[malaria]]) or by non-casual transfer of bodily fluid (such as [[blood transfusion|transfusions]], [[needle sharing]] or [[sexual intercourse|sexual contact]]).<ref>[https://www.transfusionguidelines.org/dsg/wb/guidelines/no005-non-contagious-diseases-contact-with Non-Contagious Diseases - Contact With] ''www.transfusionguidelines.org'', accessed 27 January 2020</ref>\nThe boundary between contagious and non-contagious infectious diseases is not perfectly drawn, as illustrated classically by [[tuberculosis]], which is clearly transmissible from person to person, but was not classically considered a contagious disease. In the present day, most [[sexually transmitted infection]]s are considered contagious,<!--<ref>[http://www.humanillnesses.com/Infectious-Diseases-My-Si/Sexually-Transmitted-Diseases.html  Sexually Transmitted Diseases: Sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) are infections that pass from one person to another through sexual contact, which includes oral, genital, or anal intercourse] ''www.humanillnesses.com'', accessed 27 January 2020</ref>--> but only some of them are subject to medical [[isolation (health care)|isolation]].\n\nA disease may be known to be contagious but its [[Disease causative agent|causative]] factors remain undetermined. A contagion may be more infectious if the [[incubation period]] is long.\n\n== Historical meaning ==\nOriginally, the term referred to a ''contagion'' (a derivative of 'contact') or disease transmissible only by direct physical contact. In the modern-day, the term has sometimes been broadened to encompass ''any'' communicable or infectious disease. Often the word can only be understood in context, where it is used to emphasise very [[Infection|infectious]], easily transmitted, or especially severe communicable disease.\n\nIn 1849, John Snow first proposed that cholera was a contagious disease.\n{{seealso|Diseases and epidemics of the 19th century}}\n\n== Effect on Public Health Response ==\n[[Image:NIH Clinical Center - Special Clinical Studies Unit.jpg|thumb|This clinic uses [[negative room pressure]] to prevent disease transmission]]\nMost [[epidemics]] are caused by contagious diseases, with occasional exceptions, such as [[yellow fever]]. The spread of non-contagious communicable diseases is changed either very little or not at all by medical isolation of ill persons or medical [[quarantine]] for exposed persons. Thus, a \"contagious disease\" is sometimes defined in practical terms, as a disease for which isolation or quarantine are useful public health responses.<ref>[http://www.redcross.org/preparedness/cdc_english/IsoQuar.asp A primer from the CDC on quarantine and its uses against contagious disease spread] Accessed Nov. 27, 2009.</ref>{{Not in ref|date=January 2020}}\n\nSome locations are better suited for the research into the contagious pathogens due to the reduced risk of transmission afforded by a remote or isolated location.\n\n[[Negative room pressure]] is a technique in health care facilities based on [[aerobiological engineering|aerobiological]] designs.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Germ theory of disease]]\n*[[Herd immunity]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Infectious diseases]]\n", "text_old": "{{expert needed | Medicine|date = September 2016}}\n{{Refimprove|date= September 2016}}\n\nA '''contagious disease''' is a subset category of [[Transmission (medicine)|transmissible]] [[diseases]], which are transmitted to other persons, either by physical contact with the person suffering the disease, or by casual contact with their [[secretion]]s or objects touched by them or [[airborne disease|airborne route]] among other routes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefreedictionary.com/Contagious+disease |title=Merriam-Webster dictionary definition of contagious disease |access-date=2009-11-27}}</ref>  Contagiousness varies between diseases.\n\nNon-contagious infections, by contrast, usually require a special mode of transmission between persons or [[host (biology)|host]]s. These include need for intermediate [[vector (epidemiology)|vector]] species ([[mosquito]]es that carry [[malaria]]) or by non-casual transfer of bodily fluid (such as [[blood transfusion|transfusions]], [[needle sharing]] or [[sexual intercourse|sexual contact]]).<ref>[https://www.transfusionguidelines.org/dsg/wb/guidelines/no005-non-contagious-diseases-contact-with Non-Contagious Diseases - Contact With] ''www.transfusionguidelines.org'', accessed 27 January 2020</ref>\nThe boundary between contagious and non-contagious infectious diseases is not perfectly drawn, as illustrated classically by [[tuberculosis]], which is clearly transmissible from person to person, but was not classically considered a contagious disease. In the present day, most [[sexually transmitted infection]]s are considered contagious,<!--<ref>[http://www.humanillnesses.com/Infectious-Diseases-My-Si/Sexually-Transmitted-Diseases.html  Sexually Transmitted Diseases: Sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) are infections that pass from one person to another through sexual contact, which includes oral, genital, or anal intercourse] ''www.humanillnesses.com'', accessed 27 January 2020</ref>--> but only some of them are subject to medical [[isolation (health care)|isolation]].\n\nA disease may be known to be contagious but its [[Disease causative agent|causative]] factors remain undetermined. A contagion may be more infectious if the [[incubation period]] is long.\n\n== Historical meaning ==\nOriginally, the term referred to a ''contagion'' (a derivative of 'contact') or disease transmissible only by direct physical contact. In the modern-day, the term has sometimes been broadened to encompass ''any'' communicable or infectious disease. Often the word can only be understood in context, where it is used to emphasise very [[Infection|infectious]], easily transmitted, or especially severe communicable disease.\n\nIn 1949, John Snow first proposed that cholera was a contagious disease.\n{{seealso|Diseases and epidemics of the 19th century}}\n\n== Effect on Public Health Response ==\n[[Image:NIH Clinical Center - Special Clinical Studies Unit.jpg|thumb|This clinic uses [[negative room pressure]] to prevent disease transmission]]\nMost [[epidemics]] are caused by contagious diseases, with occasional exceptions, such as [[yellow fever]]. The spread of non-contagious communicable diseases is changed either very little or not at all by medical isolation of ill persons or medical [[quarantine]] for exposed persons. Thus, a \"contagious disease\" is sometimes defined in practical terms, as a disease for which isolation or quarantine are useful public health responses.<ref>[http://www.redcross.org/preparedness/cdc_english/IsoQuar.asp A primer from the CDC on quarantine and its uses against contagious disease spread] Accessed Nov. 27, 2009.</ref>{{Not in ref|date=January 2020}}\n\nSome locations are better suited for the research into the contagious pathogens due to the reduced risk of transmission afforded by a remote or isolated location.\n\n[[Negative room pressure]] is a technique in health care facilities based on [[aerobiological engineering|aerobiological]] designs.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Germ theory of disease]]\n*[[Herd immunity]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Medicine}}\n\n[[Category:Infectious diseases]]\n", "name_user": "Drew Heffernan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed date of John Snow treatise on chol\u00e9ra to C19", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contagious_disease"}
